My Review: far too long and disjointed for what it's trying to be. the main plot isn’t really convincing, but even assuming this is just a thought experiment or meant to be taken only as allegory or whatever, I don’t know what the point here was, apart from relishing in repetitive descriptions of decay. then again, maybe I'm just bored by diatribes on how civilization is but a veneer and any city-dweller is 0.34 seconds away from snapping and going to kill and eat the neighbor's dog.

Title: The Power of Habit: Why We Do What We Do in Life and Business
Author: Charles Duhigg
My Review:
I give up. buzzwordy, annoyingly clunky, and so SO repetitive. i'm pretty sure the author assumed everyone who's reading this book has the attention span of a goldfish, because why else would he endlessly recapitulate the things that I've just read a moment ago in the next chapter? habit loop, keystone habit, blah blah blah. the audiobook for this is 10 hours, and i shudder to imagine how mind numbingly boring listening to its entirety would be. here's what you are supposed to learn from the 3-ish hours that i only tolerated because the MTA is a disaster: habits are cool, they are very useful, you can change them and it'll really really help you. some habits are more helpful than others. let me make up a name for them. here's an examp... let's talk about something else for 20 minutes... le of this person who changed his habits and all was awesome and he was like hella productive. did i mention habits are useful? yeah. let me throw in some smart sounding Latin names of brain parts and a story about some boring ass CEO and make it all really inspiring in that vomit-inducing hopeful tone that implies that YOU, the reader, can change too

bottom line: why am i doing this to myself? i don't know, but I'm giving it more than 1 star because it reminded me to make my bed and briefly consider doing yoga
